  1. The old violation code for missing city sticker is 0964125 and 0976170. The new violation code for missing city sticker is 0964125B (under/ equal to 16000LBS) . Under the old codes, the cost of an initial oﬀense was 120 dollars and it is 200 dollars under the new one.

  1. Three ticket types she should have increased: EXPIRED METER OR OVERSTAY, EXPIRED PLATES OR TEMPORARY REGISTRATION and STREET CLEANING.
    Reason: In order to maximize the revenue increase, we need to take into consideration both whether the number of issued tickets under a certain violation type is large enough and whether the repayment rate is high enough. Therefore we can construct a viable “margin” = tickets number * repayment rate, which represents how much revenue is increased if we increase the fine for the violation type by 1 dollar(Assuming there is no behavioral response). We choose EXPIRED METER OR OVERSTAY, EXPIRED PLATES OR TEMPORARY REGISTRATION and STREET CLEANING because they can provide highest margin.
for_revenue <- 
  tickets_1pct %>%
  mutate(year = str_sub(issue_date, 1, 4)) %>%
  filter(as.numeric(year) < 2012) %>%
  group_by(violation_description) %>%
  summarise(n = n(), rate_repay = sum(ticket_queue == "Paid", na.rm = TRUE)/n(), margin = n*rate_repay) %>%
  arrange(desc(margin))

print(for_revenue)

         share_black = as.numeric(HC01_EST_VC05)/100,
         median_income = as.numeric(HC01_EST_VC02)
         ) %>%
  select(zipcode, share_black, median_income)
## Warning in evalq(as.numeric(HC01_EST_VC05)/100, <environment>): 强制改变过
## 程中产生了NA
## Warning in evalq(as.numeric(HC01_EST_VC02), <environment>): 强制改变过程中
## 产生了NA
zip_joined <-
  left_join(tickets_1pct, census_data_zip, by = "zipcode")

higher_income <- zip_joined %>% filter(median_income > 25000) 
higher_income %>%  
  group_by(violation_description) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  arrange(desc(n)) %>%
  slice(1:3)
